# templates/drivers/codex.driver — the OpenAI Codex CLI driver:
#   multiplexer = herdr · agent runtime = OpenAI Codex CLI (`codex`).
#
# The FIRST non-Claude agent-runtime driver (HERD-178, agent-runtime portability epic HERD-150).
# It swaps ONLY the RUNTIME — the `claude`-specific exec surface (spawn / one-shot / resume /
# model-switch / permission-mode / limit / session / cost) is rebound to Codex's real control
# surface — while KEEPING herdr as the multiplexer, exactly as herdr-claude.driver's header notes
# ("a non-Claude runtime rebinds this block, keeping herdr as the mux"). Model this file on
# templates/drivers/herdr-claude.driver (default) + headless.driver. See docs/driver-abstraction.md.
#
# CONTRACT (mirrors .herd/config, same as every driver): shell-sourceable KEY=value, COMMITTED,
# ZERO-SECRET — command SHAPES only, never credentials or absolute host paths ({{SCRIPTS_DIR}} is
# resolved at render time). Selected per project by `.herd/config` key HERD_DRIVER=codex.
#
# RENDER SCOPE: templates/coordinator.md.tmpl tokenizes only the four MUX capabilities
# ({{DRIVER_LIST_AGENTS}} {{DRIVER_FOCUS_AGENT}} {{DRIVER_SEND_TEXT}} {{DRIVER_SWITCH_MODEL}}), which
# this driver binds to the SAME herdr surface as the default — so `HERD_DRIVER=codex herd render`
# resolves the binding table with NO missing-binding crash and NO leftover {{token}}. The
# DRIVER_AGENT_* exec block below is data the P2–P4 routing (Brian's queue) consumes; nothing renders
# it yet. Proof: tests/test-codex-driver.sh.
#
# FLAGS ARE RESEARCHED, NOT GUESSED. Every codex flag below is from the Codex CLI reference
# (developers.openai.com/codex/cli/reference): `codex [PROMPT]`, `codex exec [PROMPT]`, `--model,-m`,
# `--sandbox,-s {read-only|workspace-write|danger-full-access}`,
# `--ask-for-approval,-a {untrusted|on-request|never}`, `--dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox`
# (alias `--yolo`), `codex resume [SESSION_ID] [--last]`, and the `/model` TUI command.

# ── MUX capabilities (herdr) — IDENTICAL to herdr-claude: this driver swaps the RUNTIME, not the
#    multiplexer, so every herdr incantation below is byte-for-byte the default's. ──────────────────
DRIVER_LIST_AGENTS='herdr agent list'
DRIVER_FOCUS_AGENT='herdr agent focus <slug>'
DRIVER_SEND_TEXT='herdr pane run <agent-pane> "<text>"; herdr pane send-keys <agent-pane> Enter'
DRIVER_SWITCH_MODEL='herdr pane run <builder-agent-pane> "/model <MODEL_FEATURE value>"'

# ── MUX capabilities the LANE SCRIPTS + watcher exercise (bound so the driver covers the FULL
#    mux surface, not just the four the skill names inline). Same herdr surface as the default. ─────
DRIVER_START_AGENT='bash {{SCRIPTS_DIR}}/herd-feature.sh <slug> "<task>"'
DRIVER_CREATE_TAB='herdr tab create --workspace <ws>'
DRIVER_READ_PANE='herdr pane read <pane>'
DRIVER_SEND_KEYS='herdr pane send-keys <pane> <keys>'

# ── Agent-runtime EXEC bindings (HERD-150 P1 capability table, rebound for Codex) ─────────────────
# Each key is Codex's real incantation for its capability class — the codex counterpart of the exact
# `claude …` strings herdr-claude.driver carries. Same contract: command SHAPES only, zero-secret.
#
# ABSENT-BINDING DEGRADATION CONTRACT. A capability the runtime does NOT expose as a stable,
# verifiable contract (Codex's usage-limit banner text; the exact transcript token-usage JSON schema
# + a codex-model→USD price table) is bound to an explicit `@degrade:<reason>` sentinel rather than a
# GUESSED value. The sentinel is deliberately fail-safe on every consumer: as a regex it can never
# match real runtime output (so limit-detection simply never false-fires and falls through to the
# runtime-independent hook-sentinel + resume backstop — see docs/driver-abstraction.md § limit-
# detection); as a space-separated key list it names no real JSON field (so a usage sum finds nothing
# and cost.sh surfaces it as `unpriced`/zero, its documented graceful degrade). It is always non-empty
# so no consumer crashes under `set -u`, and self-documents WHY the capability degraded. This is the
# honest alternative to inventing a rate-limit regex or a token schema the runtime never promised.

# interactive-spawn — open a Codex TUI seeded with the task prompt, full-autonomy (bypass approvals).
DRIVER_AGENT_INTERACTIVE_SPAWN='codex --model <model> --dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox "<prompt>"'
# one-shot-exec — headless, no TUI. `codex exec` (alias `codex e`) runs non-interactively.
DRIVER_AGENT_ONESHOT_EXEC='codex exec --model <model> --dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox "<prompt>"'
# resume — reopen the most recent session in the cwd with full context (global flag precedes the
# `resume` subcommand; `--last` skips the picker). Codex analog of `claude --continue`.
DRIVER_AGENT_RESUME='codex --dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox resume --last "<prompt>"'
# model-switch — the `/model <model>` TUI slash command, delivered via the mux DRIVER_SEND_TEXT
# (same shape as Claude Code — both TUIs expose `/model`).
DRIVER_AGENT_MODEL_SWITCH='/model <model>'
# permission-mode flag — Codex's full-autonomy bypass (alias `--yolo`), the analog of Claude's
# `--dangerously-skip-permissions`. A graduated alternative is `--sandbox workspace-write
# --ask-for-approval never`; the lanes default to the bypass for a hands-off builder in an isolated
# worktree, overridable via HERD_CLAUDE_FLAGS.
DRIVER_AGENT_PERMISSION_FLAG='--dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox'
# limit-detection — DEGRADED: no verified Codex usage-limit banner. Fail-safe: never matches, so
# limit detection falls through to the runtime-independent hook sentinel + resume backstop.
DRIVER_AGENT_LIMIT_PATTERN='@degrade:no-verified-codex-usage-limit-banner'
# session-identity — Codex stores session rollouts under ~/.codex/sessions (date-sharded rollout
# JSONL), rebindable via $HERD_TRANSCRIPT_ROOT. Real Codex equivalent of Claude's ~/.claude/projects.
DRIVER_AGENT_SESSION_ID='${HERD_TRANSCRIPT_ROOT:-$HOME/.codex/sessions}/**/rollout-*.jsonl'
# cost/telemetry parse — DEGRADED: Codex's transcript token-usage JSON keys + a codex-model→USD
# price table are not a verifiable stable contract here. Fail-safe: names no real field → cost.sh
# sums nothing and marks the model `unpriced` rather than reporting a fabricated $0.
DRIVER_AGENT_COST_USAGE_KEYS='@degrade:no-verified-codex-usage-token-schema'
